      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Absolutely, and it is a good thing to keep an eye on the wording. When drafting or reviewing a durable power of attorney, look for a few key phrases that reinforce the fiduciary relationship and add layers of protection:\n\n1. **Explicit Fiduciary Duty Clause**: The document should state that the agent is a fiduciary and must act in the principal’s best interest. This is the legal backbone that makes the agent accountable.\n\n2. **Scope of Authority**: Specify exactly what actions the agent can take—e.g., buying or selling property, managing bank accounts, handling insurance claims. A clear list prevents ambiguity.\n\n3. **Reporting and Audit Provisions**: Include a clause that requires the agent to provide periodic reports (e.g., quarterly or annually) detailing transactions, balances, and any changes in the principal’s assets. This gives your dad a way to monitor the agent’s work.\n\n4. **Duration and Termination Language**: The document should clearly state how long the power of attorney remains effective and under what conditions it can be revoked or terminated.\n\n5. **Governing Law and Jurisdiction**: Adding a clause that specifies which state’s laws govern the document can help avoid confusion about the legal interpretation",
